    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
            <p>Not published before <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>125100</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><gap reason="illegible" quantity="1" unit="character"/><orig>τε</orig>
                       <gap reason="illegible" quantity="1" unit="character"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>     
                    <lb n="2"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> <supplied reason="lost">βασιλέ</supplied>ως <persName type="ruler" key="Ptolemy undetermined"><name nymRef="#Πτολεμαῖος">Π<unclear>τ</unclear><supplied reason="lost">ολεμαίου</supplied></name></persName>
                        <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                    <lb n="2a"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="line"/>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> du roi Ptolémée <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> of king Ptolemy <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> del re Tolemeo <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
               <p>The very careful cutting is a clue for a honorific inscription, either for the king himself or for some member of the royal court. The latter 
                   is the more so plausible that the two letters preserved at line 1 do not fit into a royal titulature. It is of course impossible to guess which 
                   king Ptolemy is here mentioned.</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
